SIMPLE: wicked
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wicked
<hw>Wicked</hw> <pr>(w⟦icr⟧kt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having a wick;
-- used chiefly in composition; <as>as, a two-<ex>wicked</ex>
lamp</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wicked</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wicked
<hw>Wick"ed</hw> <pr>(w⟦icr⟧k"⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wicked</ets>, fr. <ets>wicke</ets> wicked; probably originally the
same word as <ets>wicche</ets> wizard, witch. See
<er>Witch</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Evil in principle or practice; deviating from
morality; contrary to the moral or divine law; addicted to vice or sin;
sinful; immoral; profligate; -- said of persons and things; <as>as, a
<ex>wicked</ex> king; a <ex>wicked</ex> woman; a <ex>wicked</ex> deed;
<ex>wicked</ex> designs.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hence, then, and evil go with thee along,⟦br⟧
Thy offspring, to the place of evil, hell,⟦br⟧
Thou and thy <qex>wicked</qex> crew!</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Never, never, <qex>wicked</qex> man was wise.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Cursed; baneful; hurtful; bad; pernicious;
dangerous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Wicked</xex>
dew.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This were a <qex>wicked</qex> way, but whoso had a guide.</q>
<rj><qau>P. Plowman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Ludicrously or sportively mischievous; disposed to
mischief; roguish.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pen looked uncommonly <qex>wicked</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Iniquitous; sinful; criminal; guilty; immoral;
unjust; unrighteous; unholy; irreligious; ungodly; profane; vicious;
pernicious; atrocious; nefarious; heinous; flagrant; flagitious;
abandoned. See <er>Iniquitous</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wickedly</ent>⟦br⟧
